Unrestrained central bankers?
Prague—recently, a one-sided criticism of central banks in developed countries has become popular.
The main points of attack are roughly as follows: central bankers have been too active since 2008, and their powers have expanded too rapidly, causing harm to the economy.
This statement—is—strange. It is popular on both sides of the supposedly uncoordinated ideological camps, such as liberals and neo-Marxists——it's completely wrong.
Critics failed to understand that modern central banks are responsible not only for controlling inflation, but also for maintaining long-term price stability.
Price levels are like human body temperature, they can fluctuate within a normal range without causing serious symptoms.
In fighting off inflation caused by weak demand and curbing inflation driven by excessive demand, the central bank must be equally "active".
Although the battle is completely symmetrical, the public assessment of this is strangely severely biased, especially in countries where people are very conservative in finance.
This includes my home country of the Czech Republic. The Czech Republic's savers have a very small savings scale, and the loan-deposit ratio is still far below 100%.
Czechs are worried about inflation, even though the Czech inflation rate reached a 13-year low last year, and since 2013 when I have been serving as vice-governor of the Czech National Bank, we have been committed to eliminating the risk of deflation.
Other common complaints about central bank policies in developed countries since 2008 are that these policies have had redistributive effects.
Of course, it will be like this, but what's the difference?
Any monetary policy action will redistribute wealth.
Raising interest rates makes savers happy, while reducing interest rates benefits borrowers.
Importers prefer a strong exchange rate, while exporters prefer a weak exchange rate.
To be effective, monetary policy must produce different effects on different groups at different times.
This is not an error; this is the essence of monetary policy.
Some critics even say that the central bank in no case has achieved the inflation target, so their optimism is not only unnecessary, but also ineffective.
At times, they even place these contradictory criticisms in a single sentence, as if they were accusing someone of firing blanks and causing casualties.
In reality, the major central banks around the world have successfully maintained price stability and purchasing power of the currency during and after the global financial crisis — and this is an outstanding achievement.
If it weren't for their intervention, their economies would be facing a disastrous deflation, a sharp drop in asset prices, and a complete collapse of both the financial and real sectors.
Obviously, strong action is the correct approach to the crisis (what role the central bank played in the financial crisis is another issue).
In an economic system that uses a currency that lacks inherent value, in order to keep the purchasing power of a currency roughly unchanged, the amount of currency must change over time.
Therefore, price stability, not the quantity of currency, is the key issue.
The expansion of the central bank's balance sheet reflects the depth of the problems many economies faced after 2008.
In this context, the central bank has taken necessary measures to maintain purchasing power and price stability.
As for them, there is no "optimism" here; only an eternal mission to be achieved.
If you think this judgment has an air of arrogance, then let me provide some evidence.
People vote with their wallets.
If their money's purchasing power has been severely hit since 2008, they would naturally seek to exchange their currency (exchange it for other currencies, precious metals, or other savings methods)
This is rare to see in developed countries.
Of course, many central banks have failed to achieve their inflation targets.
(Central banks usually define a desired economic temperature as an inflation rate of around 2% per year.
) While this is certainly unpleasant, it will not cause a disaster, especially considering that some of the price drops are due to supply — — rather than demand — — shocks, such as a sharp drop in oil prices.
This shock is beneficial to consumers, and poses no threat to price stability, at least not for net oil importing countries.
Considering this situation.
One enterprise plans to increase 2% in sales, but the manager achieves it in the form of a continuous two-year increase of 1% per year.
Do you think this enterprise will fail?
Probably not.
After all, private company plans and actual profits and revenues may easily deviate by 10% or more.
Most enterprises' operating environment variables are less than the central bank's.
Given this, how can you expect the central bank to achieve precise inflation targets regardless of the economic environment?
Must make it clear, I did not say that the central bank should not make an effort to approach their targets.
They should absolutely do so.
Moreover, they should never make inflation expectations unstable.
However, when judging the central bank, people need to maintain appropriate proportions.
They do indeed need to stop saying things that are not true – things like the central bank's policy arsenal is not only possible to be exhausted, but is also almost exhausted.
Monetary policymakers have a sufficient arsenal of weapons and unlimited ammunition at their disposal.
These weapons have different calibers, and their effects vary at different times.
Not all weapons are suitable for all economic bodies in all situations.
But the central bank's ability to theoretically create and destroy currency is limitless.
The central bank governor should tell the critics facing ignorance, "Enough."
None of our critics can explain in a clear and trustworthy way why price stability is a wrong goal, what the central bank should pursue as a key goal; and what sharply different measures they should have taken since 2008.
There is a simple reason for this: the monetary policy adopted by developed countries' central banks since the crisis is the correct policy.
In fact, that policy pulled our economy back from the edge of a cliff.
You're welcome.
